Two episodes banked for later
"The Ones Who Got Nothing" — the human dimension: Garand (18 years, $100), Hedy Lamarr (frequency hopping → WiFi/GPS/Bluetooth, patent expired unused), Boyd (OODA Loop, Pentagon fought him his whole career), Kelly Johnson (Skunk Works), Rickover (forced out at 82), Tommy Flowers (Colossus, ordered to destroy it, silent 30 years). Ancient parallels: Archimedes killed by a Roman soldier, the anonymous trireme shipwrights of Salamis, the unnamed Antikythera engineer. Core question: does a civilization that forgets its Garands deserve its golden era?
Special inclusion — Lt. Col. Don Carlos Faith Jr., Chosin Reservoir, Nov 27–Dec 1, 1950. Threw his Silver Star into the snow when Almond pinned it and flew off. Refused to cross the reservoir until every wounded man crossed first. Mortally wounded at the final roadblock. Posthumous Medal of Honor; remains not recovered for 62 years; Arlington 2013; daughter Bobbie was 4. Anchor line: "Most men who earn the Medal of Honor survive to receive it. Faith did not. He fell at the very moment his men broke through."
"The Waste Between the Wars" — ~$36B wasted (Zumwalt, Constellation cancellation, Seawolf overruns, Iowa reactivation, Ford overruns) — roughly 14 Arleigh Burkes or 10 Virginia-class subs' worth. Roman parallel: contractors supplying substandard equipment, political class prioritizing enrichment over defense, while China builds 6–8 ships/year in the same stretch. Your thesis: this is a contributor to the fall of the American century. Counter-thread: golden era and waste can coexist — the correction may have come just in time, or not at all.
